  <h2 class="section-headline">The long way round</h2>
  <div class="body-copy">
    <p>Ben Caddy is an entrepreneur and writer based in the UK. From Bristol, through Cape Town, C&ocirc;te d&rsquo;Ivoire, Bahrain, Dubai, Bangkok, California, now Bristol again. Thirty years of standing in different rooms and watching people try to make meaning out of what&rsquo;s in front of them.</p>
    <p>That work has mostly been commercial. He built an agency in the Middle East that scaled to fifty-odd people and served some of the world&rsquo;s biggest brands. He ran a live events company that delivered cultural events at a scale that changed what people in that region thought events could be. He&rsquo;s advised the smallest startups to the United Nations, and spent the back half of his career helping founders and owners see what they couldn&rsquo;t see from inside their own thing.</p>
    <p>He currently works with a diverse portfolio of clients, is co-founder of a game studio creating collaborative storytelling products for education, and is active in helping create career pathways for young people from underserved communities.</p>
  </div>

  <blockquote class="pull-quote">&ldquo;Then find the story the situation is actually telling, in order to find the one it needs.&rdquo;</blockquote>

  <div class="body-copy">
    <p>Most of it has come down to the same instinct: stand at enough angles, and from far enough away, that the thing starts to look weird. Then find the story the situation is actually telling, in order to find the one it needs.</p>
    <p>Now he writes about that instinct: the way story runs underneath everything we think we&rsquo;re choosing, and what it costs us not to notice.</p>
  </div>
</section>
